1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,751
September, 476 AD.

2
00:00:01,751 --> 00:00:04,085
The Roman Empire falls.

3
00:00:04,085 --> 00:00:06,820
And almost nobody notices.

4
00:00:06,820 --> 00:00:09,020
No burning city. No final battle.

5
00:00:09,020 --> 00:00:12,520
Just a boy emperor,
quietly told to go home.

6
00:00:12,520 --> 00:00:14,788
Because the empire didn't die that day.

7
00:00:14,788 --> 00:00:17,540
It had been dying for three hundred years.

8
00:00:17,540 --> 00:00:19,873
This is the real story of how

9
00:00:19,873 --> 00:00:22,940
Rome collapsed, and why
everyone remembers it wrong.

10
00:00:23,380 --> 00:00:26,540
Picture the empire everyone
imagines: endless legions,

11
00:00:26,540 --> 00:00:30,000
marble cities, roads that ruled the world.

12
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:32,019
But an empire isn't marble.

13
00:00:32,019 --> 00:00:34,038
It's a machine: an army,

14
00:00:34,038 --> 00:00:36,860
paid by taxes, paid in silver.

15
00:00:36,940 --> 00:00:39,211
That army numbered somewhere between four

16
00:00:39,211 --> 00:00:42,260
hundred thousand and six
hundred thousand men.

17
00:00:42,580 --> 00:00:46,100
Soldiers expected pay and
supplies, every single year.

18
00:00:46,100 --> 00:00:49,580
Multiply that by half a million men.

19
00:00:49,900 --> 00:00:52,900
It was the single biggest
expense the Roman state had.

20
00:00:52,900 --> 00:00:54,800
And the bill kept growing.

21
00:00:55,240 --> 00:00:58,540
Break the machine that pays
that army, and you break Rome.

22
00:00:58,540 --> 00:00:59,860
So let's break it.

23
00:00:59,860 --> 00:01:01,660
Start in the year 235.

24
00:01:01,660 --> 00:01:03,820
Over the next fifty years, Rome

25
00:01:03,820 --> 00:01:06,180
burned through at least
twenty-six emperors.

26
00:01:06,180 --> 00:01:07,998
Twenty-six men in fifty years.

27
00:01:07,998 --> 00:01:10,542
The throne had stopped being a prize.

28
00:01:10,542 --> 00:01:12,660
It was a death sentence.

29
00:01:12,660 --> 00:01:15,730
Every general with an
army could crown himself.

30
00:01:15,730 --> 00:01:18,800
So every general did.
Civil war became routine.

31
00:01:18,800 --> 00:01:21,780
And while Romans fought
Romans, the borders

32
00:01:21,780 --> 00:01:25,080
went unguarded, and the treasury bled dry.

33
00:01:25,080 --> 00:01:27,278
Which brings us to the silver.

34
00:01:27,278 --> 00:01:31,340
Watch the silver, because this
is where empires really die.

35
00:01:31,760 --> 00:01:34,252
Rome's standard coin, the denarius, was

36
00:01:34,252 --> 00:01:37,560
once more than ninety percent pure silver.

37
00:01:37,880 --> 00:01:40,290
Each time an emperor ran short of cash,

38
00:01:40,290 --> 00:01:43,100
he melted the coins and added cheap metal.

39
00:01:43,340 --> 00:01:45,473
By the 270s, the denarius

40
00:01:45,473 --> 00:01:47,607
was around five percent silver.

41
00:01:47,607 --> 00:01:50,140
A shiny coating over junk.

42
00:01:50,220 --> 00:01:52,553
Imagine getting paid in coins that lose

43
00:01:52,553 --> 00:01:55,600
their value faster than
you can spend them.

44
00:01:55,600 --> 00:01:57,688
Prices exploded across the empire.

45
00:01:57,688 --> 00:01:59,775
When money itself stops being

46
00:01:59,775 --> 00:02:02,680
trusted, everything built on it wobbles.

47
00:02:03,080 --> 00:02:06,848
Emperor Diocletian tried to
fix inflation by outlawing it.

48
00:02:06,848 --> 00:02:09,480
High prices became a capital crime.

49
00:02:09,480 --> 00:02:10,929
It failed spectacularly.

50
00:02:10,929 --> 00:02:13,343
Merchants stopped selling, and goods

51
00:02:13,343 --> 00:02:16,640
simply vanished into the black market.

52
00:02:16,840 --> 00:02:20,680
Then came the part nobody
could control: disease.

53
00:02:21,120 --> 00:02:23,800
Two great plagues swept
the empire, emptying

54
00:02:23,800 --> 00:02:26,880
farms and thinning the
army's recruiting pool.

55
00:02:27,280 --> 00:02:29,587
Fewer farmers meant less tax.

56
00:02:29,587 --> 00:02:32,816
Fewer recruits meant
a more expensive army.

57
00:02:32,816 --> 00:02:34,540
The squeeze tightened.

58
00:02:34,540 --> 00:02:36,590
So Rome found a shortcut.

59
00:02:36,590 --> 00:02:40,680
If you can't recruit enough
Romans, hire the barbarians.

60
00:02:40,680 --> 00:02:42,929
Whole units now fought under their own

61
00:02:42,929 --> 00:02:45,500
chiefs, loyal to their
leaders and their paychecks.

62
00:02:45,500 --> 00:02:47,637
Not to Rome. Remember that detail.

63
00:02:47,637 --> 00:02:51,600
It comes back at the
very end of this story.

64
00:02:52,000 --> 00:02:55,435
In 378, at Adrianople,
the arrangement blew up.

65
00:02:55,435 --> 00:02:59,700
Gothic forces destroyed much
of the eastern field army.

66
00:02:59,980 --> 00:03:02,297
The emperor Valens died on that

67
00:03:02,297 --> 00:03:05,400
battlefield, along with
Rome's aura of invincibility.

68
00:03:05,740 --> 00:03:08,720
Afterward, for the first
time, entire barbarian nations

69
00:03:08,720 --> 00:03:12,020
settled inside the empire
under their own kings.

70
00:03:12,020 --> 00:03:14,505
The bargain was simple
and desperate: fight for

71
00:03:14,505 --> 00:03:17,700
us, and we'll pay you and give you land.

72
00:03:17,840 --> 00:03:20,180
Rome no longer commanded these people.

73
00:03:20,180 --> 00:03:23,700
It negotiated with them,
inside its own borders.

74
00:03:24,520 --> 00:03:27,784
In 395, the emperor Theodosius died, and

75
00:03:27,784 --> 00:03:31,514
the empire was split between his two sons.

76
00:03:31,514 --> 00:03:32,380
Permanently.

77
00:03:32,740 --> 00:03:36,040
The East got the wealth
and the defensible capital.

78
00:03:36,040 --> 00:03:38,440
The West got the exposed frontiers.

79
00:03:38,440 --> 00:03:42,040
And the West's new emperor,
Honorius, was ten years old.

80
00:03:42,040 --> 00:03:44,680
A child on the throne, a broke treasury,

81
00:03:44,680 --> 00:03:47,720
and an army that worked for whoever paid.

82
00:03:47,960 --> 00:03:50,524
Then, in 410, the unthinkable.

83
00:03:50,524 --> 00:03:52,576
Alaric's Visigoths marched into

84
00:03:52,576 --> 00:03:55,540
Rome itself and sacked it.

85
00:03:55,840 --> 00:03:57,880
The city had not fallen to a

86
00:03:57,880 --> 00:04:00,320
foreign enemy in nearly
eight hundred years.

87
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:03,360
One church father, Jerome,
wrote: the city which

88
00:04:03,360 --> 00:04:06,720
had taken the whole
world was itself taken.

89
00:04:06,740 --> 00:04:09,220
But here's the detail everyone misses:

90
00:04:09,220 --> 00:04:12,100
Rome wasn't even the capital anymore.

91
00:04:12,280 --> 00:04:14,620
The court had already
moved, first to Milan,

92
00:04:14,620 --> 00:04:17,360
and then to the safer city of Ravenna.

93
00:04:17,580 --> 00:04:21,567
The sack of 410 was a
symbol, and symbols matter.

94
00:04:21,567 --> 00:04:23,960
But symbols don't pay armies.

95
00:04:24,120 --> 00:04:26,630
Because the real death
blow came a generation

96
00:04:26,630 --> 00:04:29,540
later, and almost no one talks about it.

97
00:04:29,650 --> 00:04:32,378
In 439, the Vandals captured Carthage,

98
00:04:32,378 --> 00:04:35,960
the crown jewel of Roman North Africa.

99
00:04:36,040 --> 00:04:38,170
Africa fed the West with grain

100
00:04:38,170 --> 00:04:40,700
and filled its treasury with taxes.

101
00:04:41,360 --> 00:04:44,375
Lose Africa, and the math stops working.

102
00:04:44,375 --> 00:04:48,220
No taxes, no army. No army, no empire.

103
00:04:48,580 --> 00:04:50,754
This is the equation historians point

104
00:04:50,754 --> 00:04:53,291
to: the West didn't lose its will.

105
00:04:53,291 --> 00:04:55,140
It lost its income.

106
00:04:55,220 --> 00:04:58,072
As the fifth century
wore on, province after

107
00:04:58,072 --> 00:05:01,680
province slipped away, taking
the tax base with them.

108
00:05:01,820 --> 00:05:04,592
Every lost province
meant fewer taxes, which

109
00:05:04,592 --> 00:05:08,160
meant fewer soldiers, which
meant more lost provinces.

110
00:05:08,680 --> 00:05:11,399
The Western Empire now
had an army it could

111
00:05:11,399 --> 00:05:14,820
not pay, made of men whose
loyalty was for sale.

112
00:05:15,120 --> 00:05:17,800
Which brings us back to 476, and

113
00:05:17,800 --> 00:05:20,880
the fall that wasn't really a fall.

114
00:05:21,120 --> 00:05:24,018
The emperor was Romulus Augustulus, a

115
00:05:24,018 --> 00:05:27,800
boy named, incredibly,
after Rome's own founder.

116
00:05:27,860 --> 00:05:30,850
History even remembers him by a

117
00:05:30,850 --> 00:05:34,240
mocking nickname: Augustulus,
the little Augustus.

118
00:05:34,420 --> 00:05:38,276
The men who ended his reign weren't
invaders storming the gates.

119
00:05:38,276 --> 00:05:40,780
They were Rome's own federate soldiers.

120
00:05:40,820 --> 00:05:44,100
They had asked for land
in Italy to settle on.

121
00:05:44,100 --> 00:05:46,140
Their general, Orestes, said no.

122
00:05:46,340 --> 00:05:48,920
So they mutinied, chose
their commander Odoacer

123
00:05:48,920 --> 00:05:51,900
as king, and deposed the boy emperor.

124
00:05:52,020 --> 00:05:53,829
No successor was named.

125
00:05:53,829 --> 00:05:55,638
The imperial insignia were

126
00:05:55,638 --> 00:05:58,300
simply sent east, to Constantinople.

127
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:02,555
Odoacer didn't even bother to claim
the imperial title for himself.

128
00:06:02,555 --> 00:06:04,160
He didn't need it.

129
00:06:04,360 --> 00:06:06,590
The Roman Empire in the West ended not

130
00:06:06,590 --> 00:06:09,220
with a battle, but with a payroll dispute.

131
00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:13,300
And here's the strangest part:
in Italy, life simply went on.

132
00:06:14,040 --> 00:06:17,556
Odoacer kept the Roman administration.
The Senate kept meeting.

133
00:06:17,556 --> 00:06:20,200
Latin remained the language of government.

134
00:06:20,200 --> 00:06:23,240
The fall of Rome, the moment every

135
00:06:23,240 --> 00:06:26,680
textbook circles, happened
without most Romans noticing.

136
00:06:26,820 --> 00:06:30,302
Because empires don't
die the way movies show.

137
00:06:30,302 --> 00:06:34,620
They rot quietly: money first,
then loyalty, then everything.

138
00:06:34,900 --> 00:06:37,798
And half of Rome never fell at all.

139
00:06:37,798 --> 00:06:41,820
The Eastern Empire carried on
for nearly a thousand years.

140
00:06:41,900 --> 00:06:45,409
Roman emperors ruled from
Constantinople until 1453,

141
00:06:45,409 --> 00:06:47,415
almost a millennium after

142
00:06:47,415 --> 00:06:49,820
the West quietly faded.

143
00:06:49,960 --> 00:06:51,435
So Rome didn't fall.

144
00:06:51,435 --> 00:06:53,647
It faded, so slowly that the

145
00:06:53,647 --> 00:06:56,260
fall itself was just a formality.

146
00:06:56,280 --> 00:06:58,230
If this changed how you see

147
00:06:58,230 --> 00:07:00,505
history, there's more
where that came from.

148
00:07:00,505 --> 00:07:02,130
Subscribe for the next story.
